00:52:26.710 --> 00:52:29.410
- [Audience Member] I do recall that they,

00:52:29.410 --> 00:52:32.910
they kicked up some, it
looked like a white stuff

00:52:32.910 --> 00:52:36.723
on the tracks, it looked
like a salt or ice,

00:52:38.443 --> 00:52:40.710
was it actually liquid water ice?

00:52:40.710 --> 00:52:42.810
- No, we have not found ice at all

00:52:42.810 --> 00:52:44.856
with either one of the rovers,

00:52:44.856 --> 00:52:46.540
we, as you saw with Spirit,

00:52:46.540 --> 00:52:48.140
we did have that very bright stuff,

00:52:48.140 --> 00:52:50.110
that turned out to be silica.

00:52:50.110 --> 00:52:51.720
There have been other places where

00:52:51.720 --> 00:52:54.480
what we have found turned
out to be sulfate salts,

00:52:54.480 --> 00:52:56.300
but nowhere have we found ice.

00:52:56.300 --> 00:52:57.133
- [Audience Member] Thank you.

00:52:57.133 --> 00:52:58.420
- We're pretty close
to the equator on Mars

00:52:58.420 --> 00:53:01.730
and so you wouldn't really
expect it, it's too warm there.

00:53:01.730 --> 00:53:06.730
The Phoenix lander, which landed
78 degrees north latitude,

00:53:07.720 --> 00:53:11.730
was able to dig into the
soil with it's robotic arm,

00:53:11.730 --> 00:53:13.850
and five centimeters below the surface,

00:53:13.850 --> 00:53:16.100
found bright deposits of ice.

00:53:16.100 --> 00:53:18.386
So that's been done, but
that's closer to the pole.

00:53:18.386 --> 00:53:19.385
- [Audience Member] That was ice.

00:53:19.385 --> 00:53:22.276
- That was ice, yes, that was
a different mission. Yeah.

00:53:22.276 --> 00:53:23.370
- [Audience Member 2] 120 meters per day

00:53:23.370 --> 00:53:25.230
is very impressive for a machine

00:53:25.230 --> 00:53:27.300
on Mars but for us here on Earth

00:53:27.300 --> 00:53:28.580
we could walk that in a few minutes,

00:53:28.580 --> 00:53:30.890
so I'm curious how does
the rover spend it's time

00:53:30.890 --> 00:53:32.240
does it spend a lot of time thinking where

00:53:32.240 --> 00:53:33.183
it's going next?

00:53:35.100 --> 00:53:36.720
- Yeah, that's part of it, it depends on

00:53:36.720 --> 00:53:37.760
where you are in the drive.

00:53:37.760 --> 00:53:40.430
So why can you only do
about 120 meters a day.

00:53:40.430 --> 00:53:43.810
Fundamentally we're limited by power.

00:53:43.810 --> 00:53:45.790
Right now the solar arrays on Opportunity

00:53:45.790 --> 00:53:46.933
are pretty dusty,

00:53:47.900 --> 00:53:52.190
right now Opportunity's got
about 400 watt hours per cell.

00:53:52.190 --> 00:53:54.060
It's 400 watt hours to do everything,

00:53:54.060 --> 00:53:55.980
all of the driving, all the computing,

00:53:55.980 --> 00:53:58.760
taking the images,
transmitting the data to Earth,

00:53:58.760 --> 00:54:00.450
running the heaters to keep the vehicle

00:54:00.450 --> 00:54:02.360
warm at night, et cetera.

00:54:02.360 --> 00:54:04.210
So we're fundamentally power limited.

00:54:05.190 --> 00:54:08.740
The way we drive the vehicle
is the first part of the drive,

00:54:08.740 --> 00:54:11.660
we will just simply command
it, we call it blind driving,

00:54:11.660 --> 00:54:13.940
and what it means is we
know the terrain is safe

00:54:13.940 --> 00:54:15.740
we just say rover, go,

00:54:15.740 --> 00:54:17.920
and it will just drive
at top speed you apply

00:54:17.920 --> 00:54:19.370
full voltage to the wheels,

00:54:19.370 --> 00:54:21.067
you get about six centimeters a second.

00:54:21.067 --> 00:54:22.980
And that's how fast it goes.

00:54:22.980 --> 00:54:25.720
Once we've gone about 80 meters out,

00:54:25.720 --> 00:54:28.120
then we've driven so far
that the images are not

00:54:28.120 --> 00:54:31.300
good enough to recognize
potential obstacles

00:54:31.300 --> 00:54:33.900
and that's when we turn on that automatic

00:54:33.900 --> 00:54:35.253
hazard avoiding stuff.

00:54:37.066 --> 00:54:38.630
When the rover's doing that it is

00:54:38.630 --> 00:54:40.773
excruciatingly slow.

00:54:42.040 --> 00:54:43.600
You can watch one of these rovers,

00:54:43.600 --> 00:54:44.820
we've tested them on Earth and it will

00:54:44.820 --> 00:54:47.960
go like this, and it'll
stop and take a picture,

00:54:47.960 --> 00:54:51.100
and it'll think for
two and a half minutes,

00:54:51.100 --> 00:54:53.270
about what to do before it will move on.

00:54:53.270 --> 00:54:57.700
The computer inside this rover

00:54:57.700 --> 00:55:01.100
was a smoking hot machine in about 1987.

00:55:01.100 --> 00:55:02.600
It runs at a screaming 10mips.

00:55:04.300 --> 00:55:08.250
And so the rover's, I mean
your cellphone is a lot smarter

00:55:08.250 --> 00:55:09.380
than my rovers.

00:55:09.380 --> 00:55:10.830
My rovers are on Mars though.

00:55:12.770 --> 00:55:14.930
And so it's excruciatingly slow

00:55:14.930 --> 00:55:16.250
but yeah we're fundamentally limited

00:55:16.250 --> 00:55:17.520
by how much power we have.

00:55:17.520 --> 00:55:20.090
If the solar rays were completely clean

00:55:20.090 --> 00:55:22.592
we'd be able to get more mileage per day.

00:55:22.592 --> 00:55:23.593
- [Audience Member 2] Thank you.

00:55:23.593 --> 00:55:24.676
- Yeah, sure.

