00:55:31.280 --> 00:55:33.050
I had wondered from the beginning of

00:55:33.050 --> 00:55:34.870
the Mars Exploration Program,

00:55:34.870 --> 00:55:39.729
why microscopes were not
put on the earliest rovers.

00:55:39.729 --> 00:55:42.240
- Yeah, the microscopes,

00:55:42.240 --> 00:55:45.010
it has been one of the most
fundamentally useful things

00:55:45.010 --> 00:55:45.843
on our payload.

00:55:45.843 --> 00:55:47.460
I think the answer to your question is,

00:55:47.460 --> 00:55:49.090
I mean recognize there
weren't too many missions

00:55:49.090 --> 00:55:50.720
that preceded ours.

00:55:50.720 --> 00:55:52.590
There were the two Viking landers,

00:55:52.590 --> 00:55:56.330
Viking was fundamentally about looking for

00:55:56.330 --> 00:55:59.390
microbial life in the soil,

00:55:59.390 --> 00:56:01.850
and rather than a
microscopic approach to that

00:56:01.850 --> 00:56:04.670
which is very difficult with even soil

00:56:04.670 --> 00:56:06.480
samples on Earth, I mean you'd need an

00:56:06.480 --> 00:56:08.620
electron microscope to do it properly,

00:56:08.620 --> 00:56:10.860
which is very hard to do for space,

00:56:10.860 --> 00:56:13.220
the approach they took
was a set of experiments

00:56:13.220 --> 00:56:15.240
that you would look at a labeled release

00:56:15.240 --> 00:56:16.830
experiment where you'd feed it a nutrient

00:56:16.830 --> 00:56:19.050
and look at the gases come off.

00:56:19.050 --> 00:56:21.400
The next mission was Mars Pathfinder,

00:56:21.400 --> 00:56:24.240
and that was fundamentally
an engineering mission

00:56:24.240 --> 00:56:25.467
that wasn't really about science at all

00:56:25.467 --> 00:56:27.554
and the next mission after that was us,

00:56:27.554 --> 00:56:29.615
so, it kind of makes sense.

00:56:29.615 --> 00:56:31.500
